Answer:

Hmm from what I remember in probability independence has something to do with one event not affecting the other. Let me think about how that translates into a mathematical definition.  I recall that for two events A and B if knowing whether one occurs doesn't change the probability of the other occurring they're independent. So mathematically that should mean P(A|B) equals P(A) right? Because if knowing B happened doesn't change the probability of A then they're independent.  Alternatively I think there's another way to express this without conditional probabilities. Maybe it has something to do with the joint probability of both events happening. Oh yeah I think that for independent events the probability of both A and B occurring is just the product of their individual probabilities. So P(A ∩ B) should equal P(A) times P(B).  Wait let me double-check if these two statements are equivalent. If P(A|B) = P(A) then multiplying both sides by P(B) gives P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B). Yes that makes sense. So either condition can be used to determine independence.  I should also consider some examples to solidify this understanding. For instance flipping a coin twice: the result of the first flip doesn't affect the second. So if A is getting heads on the first flip and B is getting heads on the second then P(A) = 0.5 P(B) = 0.5 and P(A ∩ B) = 0.25 which is equal to 0.5 * 0.5. That checks out.  On the other hand if I draw two cards from a deck without replacement are they independent? Well let's say A is drawing an ace first and B is drawing a spade second. Then P(A) = 4/52 and P(B|A) would be different because one card has been removed. So in this case the events aren't independent. No I think without replacement each draw affects the next so they are dependent. Only with replacement would they be independent.  So in summary independence is when the occurrence of one event doesn't influence the probability of the other. This is quantified either by P(A|B) = P(A) or equivalently by P(A ∩ B) = P(A)P(B). These are the two conditions that must hold true for events to be independent.  I think I've got a good grasp now. It's important to note that independence doesn't mean the events can't happen together; it just means that one doesn't influence the probability of the other.  Two events A and B are said to be independent if the occurrence of one does not affect the probability of the occurrence of the other. Mathematically this is expressed as:  - **Conditional Probability**: The probability of event A occurring given that B has occurred is equal to the probability of A alone:   \[ P(A|B) = P(A) \]  - **Joint Probability**: The probability of both events A and B occurring together is equal to the product of their individual probabilities:   \[ P(A \cap B) = P(A) \times P(B) \]  These conditions are equivalent and either can be used to determine if two events are independent.
